Comments:
These practices are becoming a daily ritual for me, and being able to repeat these familiar steps gives me a place to rest from the chaos of life. The process of singing along with the music and the freedom of imagination is always very enjoyable, I feel relaxed and my body stretches out more.
I have to say that the effectiveness of the exercises is also very much influenced by the mood of the day, and a positive or negative initial state can affect the attention being paidand efficiency of the exercises. So I have also started to record my mood evaluations before and after practice in order to better profile my emotions.
Furthermore, one of my confusions is that although this brings emotional relief and satisfaction, does it last long enough? My observation so far is that the high level of pleasure and satisfaction almost recedes 1 to 2 hours after the practice. The gap between reality and imagination brings about even more emotional depression as I get back to the hectic schedule and deal with the difficult issues in my life. Is there a more sensible way to manage imagination about the SAT, and can imagination really soothe people? Perhaps I'll explore this more in the next exercises.

Comments:
I first select the most favourable song and then put on VR. Music really grabs my attention, especially strong rhythmic music that can get me into the zone.
When I'm done, I give myself another 20-30 minutes to think and let my imagination wander for a while. I feel that I have entered the flow state. I can feel that my brain is working at a high speed, thinking about some life insights and philosophies recalled from memories. Although most of the moments recalled still leave a deep impression and are about unhappy incidents, it is a very enjoyable feeling. Flow state is not so easy for me to enter, and I do not have the ability to flexibly enter or leave flow state in any occasion to achieve the purpose of high performance. My last high-quality flow state experience was a long period of immersion learning last year. Today's experience surprised me

Comments:
Today was a postponed exercise and it became apparent to me that imagination can be hindered when the brain is used excessively throughout the day. Because I have been studying for a long time and using my brain to a very high degree, it feels like the neurons in my brain are saturated with the connections that have been made, leaving very little room for imagination. As for the content of practice, I've had this preference for establishing pieces of the house in my head since I was little. It was more a matter of choosing my favourite pictures of housing interiors, such as design images for rooms, furniture and decorations. Then I always found the one I was most satisfied with and carefully saved them. That said, this exercise was quite familiar to me and I was able to relate it particularly well to those actions mine as a child. Although it is clear that today's exercise felt overwhelming, as brain and mind power tended to be near saturated and imagination was hindered. I would say that when I think about too many things in a day, having already made a lot of connections in the learning and thinking process, the parts left for my imagination to play with are somewhat limited. In other words, I can't really imagine what some specific house would look like, and concentrating on immersing myself in trying to come up with this house currently has some minor hindrances. But I'm sure this exercise is easy, I'm just saying it's been a bit busy lately.
A detail worth mentioning is that perhaps it's because of the connection I've built up with the kid over the last few weeks, coupled with my current state of emotional stress and anxiety, it seems that in the last few days I have returned to that fearful mental state of childhood ( although not when I was practising). I woke up one morning with a sudden recall of some of the anxiety and panic I had as a child due to fear of reprimand from parents and teachers.

Comments: On the way home late in the evening I once again made a connection with the dark sky, or more precisely the moon. The moon guided me all the way home from school, shining pure and bright overhead. I was reminded of the regularity of the moon phases and was grateful to be lucky enough to see it at this time on the lunar calendar. At the same time, it immediately reminded me of the journey I was on when I was reading the book The Moon and Sixpence. It is interesting to note that the question of the moon or sixpence is one that I have not been able to give a definitive answer to until now. The company of the moon on the way home and these deep thoughts have opened my perspective on life a little.

Comments:
Adding the singing practice really makes the experience more immersive. I grew up studying vocal singing and I got used to listening to opera to relieve my emotions at a very early age. Music is like an isolated Garden of Eden for me, an escape from the distractions of life and a steady comfort to my mood. So being able to sing and interact with my avatar really adds to my enjoyment and stimulates my imagination. The strong melodies not only stirred my emotions but also brought back memories of when I first started listening to this music as a child. Overall, it helped me to connect with the children.
Afterwards, it was almost natural to say "I passionately love you and deeply care for you!" to the children, like a musical theatre actor singing the dialogue with plenty of emotion. It was pretty much a very enjoyable experience.

Comments: This is the VR exercise I did when I got home, and this time my imagination of the ideal house went sort of well. The house I imagined to represent security was a strong house made of reinforced concrete. It is cold but strong, a symbol of strength and toughness that fits my mind. Perhaps it is perverse that I do not tend to think of a warm and cozy house, but rather a real, solid house backed up by reality as my safe house. It is probably because of this imagery that even if the house has a crumbling basement, it is unlikely to collapse. One observation was that the house I imagined would always be far away from me. Even if I deliberately tried to imagine being close to that safe house and then followed the child into it, I waited for this child to go in and I don't take a step forward into it, I felt that the house is always far away from me.

Comments: For the imagination of building out my inner house, I let myself imagine a house with a beautiful garden. But this image has led me to another period of deep thought. When I was a teenager, I struggled with the question of whether to pursue my dreams or to pursue the most successful development in the social sense. Again with the garden, an analogy that I was very indulged in at the time was that my hobby was a backyard garden and my life was the house itself. I played in my little garden, cultivated flowers and sang to my heart's content, but when the sun went down, I always had to go back to the house and live a normal functioning life. In those days, I was overwhelmed by regret and resignation, and I often repaired and regained my motivation in the "Garden of Eden" of my spiritual world, which in a sense made up for one of the gaps in my heart. I find that until now, making connections with the child often takes me back to memories of the same themes, pointing to the same causes, whether it's the moon or sixpence, the Garden of Eden or real life.

Comments: Extra practice with music today. I was planning to allocate my break time when it coincidentally occurred to me that I could do an extra practice. It was probably due to the sense of responsibility built up for the child, and overall it was enjoyable and felt like time was slipping away quite quickly. With this child, I can sense that my emotions affect the way I look at her. Even if she is in the same emotional state every time, I tend to think she is also a bit sad when I am in a low emotional state and I tend to start saying comforting words to her. The conversation usually starts about previous life lessons I learned and to convince her that there will be a turnaround. Before the exercise, I was more responsibility driven and wanted to use my imagination to develop an image of the ideal child, after the exercise I realised that the conversations I was having were probably me trying to comfort myself.  As for the change in my mood, before I started I had been anxious and nervous from the beginning of the day. To be honest I was a little stressed at first because of the responsibility I had for the child and the need to review the practice. After completing this session I got into a very calm state and my thoughts were clear. I am now a little more positive about the exercise, although I was a little sceptical at first that it was an escape from reality, today's experience shows that it is helping. (Follow-up: I then regained my motivation and continued with another round of study)

Comments: Took some time out from a busy study life to pledge to the child. I took off the VR halfway through because I didn't have a script memorised, and then read the vows before returning to the VR environment. After that I felt a very powerful sense of responsibility towards her and felt that I should take care of her and educate her, in the one that I hoped I could have become. During this time I could feel that I was more and more thinking of her as a younger me, and perhaps it was a credit to my imagination that I even felt that she resembled my personality as a little girl.
